      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Being a pioneer, so to speak, you can clear the land of an overabundance of trees, rocks and even puddles/lakes. Your materials that you gather can then be used in a much more extensive crafting system akin to that of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Animal Crossing: New Horizons",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ". It's a welcomed additon, but it leads me to a glaring negative.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "I (and maybe this is just me) ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "cannot stand",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " clunky item management in simulation games (or most games, for that matter). You begin with 16 empty slots and like all other ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Story of Seasons",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " games, you can upgrade your bag for more. However with the newly expanded crafting system in this entry, it simply makes the concept feel like even more of a burden. The developers at Marvelous did try to ease the pressure a little by creating a separate Tool Bag but in order to use the tools, you have to take them out of the Tool Bag to put them into your inventory, which can create a lot of unnecessary shuffling. Why not just let you have two separate bags? That just seems obvious to me.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "src": "__GHOST_URL__/content/images/2021/03/image-3.png",
        "width": 1280,
        "height": 720
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "However with all that aside, ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Pioneers of Olive Town",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " bursts with charm and its hook of exploring more of the unknown land will provide a sense of accomplishment that'll keep you coming back for more. Another dynamic addition is the camera where you can take first-person snapshots of animals and environements. This is an ingenious feature when you're clearing the land as you'll come across many critters and secrets throughout your adventure.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Lastly, the graphics are much more (to use the same term once more) dynamic. Cutscenes have more thought put into them and it helps to provide the town with more depth. The soundtrack is as bubbly as ever but it's also just as repetitive. You get a new soundtrack every season and while they may come as reliefs when the first day of the season rolls around, you'll soon get pretty sick of them too.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
